<p><b>Zhang Yimou</b> (born November 14, 1951) is an internationally acclaimed <a href="/wiki/China" title="China">Chinese</a> <a href="/wiki/Filmmaker" title="Filmmaker" class="mw-redirect">filmmaker</a> and former <a href="/wiki/Cinematographer" title="Cinematographer">cinematographer</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-Tasker_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Tasker-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> and one of the best known of the Fifth Generation of Chinese film directors.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> He made his directorial debut in 1987 with the <a href="/wiki/Film" title="Film">film</a> <i><a href="/wiki/Red_Sorghum" title="Red Sorghum">Red Sorghum</a></i>. One of Zhang's recurrent themes is a celebration of the resilience, even the stubbornness, of Chinese people in the face of hardships and adversities, a theme which has occurred from <i><a href="/wiki/To_Live_(film)" title="To Live (film)">To Live</a></i> (1994) through to <i><a href="/wiki/Not_One_Less" title="Not One Less">Not One Less</a></i> (1999). His works are particularly noted for their usage of colour, as can be seen in his early trilogy (like <i><a href="/wiki/Raise_the_Red_Lantern" title="Raise the Red Lantern">Raise the Red Lantern</a></i>) or in his <a href="/wiki/Wuxia" title="Wuxia">wuxia</a> films such as <i><a href="/wiki/Hero_(2002_film)" title="Hero (2002 film)">Hero</a></i> and <i><a href="/wiki/House_of_Flying_Daggers" title="House of Flying Daggers">House of Flying Daggers</a></i>.</p>
